 shows a graphic representation of the setup.
 The connection between the agent and the environment (A
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

E) represent the agent's capacity to affect (or manipulate) its environment.
 More precisely, it represents the agent's capacity to manipulate its relationsh
ip to the environment, including its location in it.
 Hence it stands for the agent's motor skills (of whichever kind and very
 broadly conceived).
 In perhaps the simplest possible case, it may stand for the agent's capacity
 to move around and therefore change its relative position within a given
 environment.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This definition is so general to actually include any kind of relative movement,
 whether the agent is endowed with locomotion or not.
 For instance a plant's leaf capacity to turn in the direction of the incoming
 light during phototropism is as valid a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

motor action
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as a bacterium's flagellate action during chemotaxis.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Conversely, the connection between the environment and the agent (E
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

A) represents the environment's capacity to affect or, more generally, somewhat
 influence the agent.
 To be more precise, E
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

A represents the possible action of the environment upon the agent from
 the 
\emph on
agent's point of view
\emph default
.
 In other words, it represents those changes in the environment that the
 agent is open to: it stands for some kind of sensory channel, very broadly
 conceived.
 The A
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

A connection represents some kind of self-limiting (if its value is negative)
 or self-amplifying (if positive) control of the agent upon itself and its
 value may be zero (i.e.
 it may not exist).
 Similarly, the E
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

E connection represents some kind of self-limiting/self-amplifying control
 of the environment upon itself, as it were (or, in an alternate reading,
 of the agent's sensitivity to the environment.
 See below section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:2-unit-equivalent"

\end_inset

).
