There are 4 parameters describing this simple 2 units setup, corresponding
 to the weights of the four connections just listed.
 Additionally, there is another set of 2nd order parameters describing how
 the previous 4 may be modified.
 For simplicity, and in or order to stay close to Ashby's original experiment,
 we consider this second set of parameters to consist of just a series of
 binary values specifying whether each one of the 4 possible connection
 is subject to an automatic resetting when the unit's value exceed its limits.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In general, this is not necessarily the case.
 The second-order feedback loop that modifies the values of the first-order
 connection may be controlled by numerous parameters, such as the amount
 of time-delay (how often the unit's variable is checked), the function
 used to change the first-order parameters, and so on.
 However, these parameters were hard-wired in Ashby's physical machine,
 hence the reduction of this second-order parameters to a binary value.
\end_layout

\end_inset

