One unit equivalent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When converting Ashby's setup to a real physical setting, the first choice
 is to to eliminate the unit corresponding to the Environment and to replace
 it with environment itself.
 The choice seems natural because it takes the equilibrium value of the
 Agent unit as the only meaningful equilibrium in the system, therefore
 eliminating the Environment unit and its associated equilibrium.
 On the other hand, the choice is not without its problems.
 First, the Homeostat did indeed have two units and 2 associated equilibrium
 values---it seems we are discarding some important element that was perhaps
 not properly discussed earlier.
 Second, this choice seem to run into an obvious issue when scaled up.
 Imagine a system with several motor and input channels all connected to
 an agent.
 In a classic Ashbian representation, the system would be modeled as a Homeostat
 comprising several units.
 In this translation, however, all the units except the agent would disappear,
 and we would have a one unit Homeostat.
 This seems unsatisfactory and needs further discussion.
 This section explores this choice before moving to a discussion of an alternati
ve.
\end_layout

