The Agent unit is therefore the only unit left.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $A\rightarrow E$
\end_inset

 connection is some form of motor action capable of modifying the relationship
 between the agent and the environment.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $E\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

 connection, in turn, is some form of sensory input from the environment.
 What about the other 2 connections in the original Homeostat? The 
\begin_inset Formula $A\rightarrow A$
\end_inset

 connection remain.
 It represents the self-control of the agent.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $E\rightarrow E$
\end_inset

 connection, instead, should be gone as well.
 It could be interpreted as a feedback loop on the sensory input source,
 roughly acting as a self-amplifier or self-damping factor.
 But in that case it would be a second 
\noun on
Homeo
\noun default
 unit, the first one representing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

motor neuron
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the second one representing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensor neuron.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This possibility is discussed below.
 Notice that this possibility seems to correspond, in Ashby's terms, to
 a 3-Unit Homeostat connected in series, and not to to a 2-Unit one.
 
