\begin_layout Standard
In general, the outgoing, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

motor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 outputs of a unit corresponds to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

open
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 connections.
 That is, they correspond to connections that go outside of the homeostat.
 Similarly, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inputs correspond to open connections that 
\emph on
come from
\emph default
 outside the homeostat.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The scare quotes are needed because the designated 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is always relative to the specific system the homeostat is modeling and
 can be the organism's environment as well as another system of the organism
 itself.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Motor output
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensory input
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be interpreted as any kind of action exerted upon or, respectively,
 input coming from the outside.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Now for the implementation of this setup in the 
\noun on
Homeo
\noun default
 system.
 Open-ended connections such as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

motor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 ones are not currently possible in 
\noun on
Homeo
\noun default
, all connections requiring a unit to connect to.
 That means that we need to introduce a special kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

output and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

input
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 units, which correspond to sensory input and motor outlets.
 In other words, they correspond to real motor drivers and sensory apparatus
 in a robotic setup (real or virtual).
 They have no uniselectors, but they do have connections.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Input units
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be connected to the units they give the input to, obviously.
 In the current 
\noun on
Homeo
\noun default
 setup, this means that they must be connectable from the receiving unit
 and that at every cycle they must produce a value to pass on.
 As this value must come from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 itself, each input unit must contain an interface to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sensory organ
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of some kind that reads that value from the world.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Output units,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 similarly, must be connected in order to receive a value to pass on the
 output equipment.
 They must as well contain an interface to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real world.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 At each cycle, this interface will simply transmit to the world the unit's
 value.
