\emph on
several 
\emph default
\noun on
ctrnn
\noun default
's neurons, even though the overall behavior of the net would have to follow
 the ultrastability/general homestasis principles the real homeostat follows.
 Check out, for instance, the early description by Beer and Gallagher 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "BeerGallagher1992"

\end_inset

, where the agent performing the chemotaxis task they describe is implemented
 in terms of 6 neurons: 2 sensory neurons, two motor neurons and 
\emph on
two fully connected internal neurons
\emph default
.
 In Ashby's terms, we would have to decide which of the subcollections of
 neurons actually represents an ultrastable homeostat 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unit.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The internal 2-neurons network? The whole assemblage? The 2+2 subunit of
 effectors+internal neurons?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the one-neuron first translation depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:First-translation"

\end_inset

.
 This organism will only receive an input from the outside world and will
 try to minimize it at all costs, operating on its effector.
 Since the input represents some stimulus from the outside (intensity of
 a chemical gradient, or of a light gradient, etcetera), the organism will
 run away from it and be a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gradient darkness-seeker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or, in Braitenberg's terms, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shy creature.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Viceversa, if the stimulus consists in a proximity value (e.g.
 from a proximity sensor), the organism will be a very primitive 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roamer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: it will try to move away from obstacles (in a very limited fashion, of
 course, given the unidimensionality of its effector).
 
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
However, consider that it is impossible to design an organism with the opposite
 behavior and identical setup.
 In other words: no change of parameters will ever turn a (gradient) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

darkness-seeker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 into a (gradient) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light seeker.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Given that the input from a chemical/light sensor is positive, the creature
 will always run away from it.
 Viceversa for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roamer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: it is impossible to turn into a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sticker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that will look for objects and cling to them.
 The only way to change the behavior of the organism is to change the physical/b
iological nature of the sensory input coming into it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This conclusion may mean that an increase in flexibility may require a different
 and more complex setup.
 For instance, it may mean that the sensitivity to chemical/photo stimuli
 must first be converted into a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proximity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measure (which may just be the reciprocal of the stimulus, roughly speaking).
 And this means that a neural apparatus (perhaps a self-standing homeostat?)
 has to be devoted to it.
 Perhaps a 2-neuron agent such as the one depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Second-translation"

\end_inset

, equivalent to a 3-unit homeostat, will be sufficient?
\end_layout

